{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KBfd9arGB7yyHi8aqEiFfp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive view of the cluster. Let me compose the change/migration plan:\n\n**Current State:**\n\n1. **Controller Version:** ingress-nginx v1.11.1\n   - Image: `registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.11.1@sha256:e6439a12b52076965928e83b7b56aae6731231677b01e81818bce7fa5c60161a`\n\n2. **Controller Args (non-default):**\n   - `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` — non-default, watches Ingress resources without ingressClassName\n   - `--enable-metrics=false` — non-default, metrics disabled\n   - `--publish-status-address=localhost` — non-default, publishes localhost as load balancer IP\n   - Several standard arguments for election, controller class, ingress class, configmap, and webhook configuration\n\nThe ConfigMap has a couple of notable settings: snippet annotations are disabled for security, and the rate limit response code is set to 429 instead of the default 503. The deployment targets nodes with the `ingress-ready` label and Linux OS, with tolerations for both master and control-plane taints. Resource requests are minimal (100m CPU, 90Mi memory) with no limits defined.\n\nThe service exposes ports 80 and 443 through NodePort mappings. In the demo namespace, there are two ingress resources: one for the demo app that rewrites `/app` requests to root, and another for the rate-limited API that enforces a 1 request-per-second limit with a burst multiplier.\n\nThere's also a health check endpoint on the same rate-limited host that bypasses rate limiting, plus two canary ingress resources sharing the same host where the stable backend routes to `stable-echo-primary` and the canary backend uses weighted traffic splitting annotations. Defining more ingress resources...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the upgrade path from v1.11.1 to v1.12.x, which means reviewing the release notes for any breaking changes, backing up the current setup, and updating the image tag to the new version.\n\nThe critical settings I need to preserve or verify compatibility for include the controller arguments like the ingress-without-class flag and metrics settings, the ConfigMap security options around snippet annotations and rate-limit status codes, and the various ingress annotations that might have changed behavior between versions.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the upgrade strategy: I'll start with a pre-upgrade snapshot of the current configuration, then review the release notes to identify any breaking changes, verify that all my custom settings are still supported in the target version, and finally execute the upgrade with a plan to test the ingress annotations afterward.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1106,"cache_read_input_tokens":36612,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1106},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2b9bd144-0083-40e9-8402-c45a67a518ad","uuid":"ccfe3ebb-f53c-4551-9021-50238bcea289","request_id":"req_011Cc6nujuqnfCuJPE1ecqYF"}
